<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-155-102 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 730 913</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 13 1991 v25 n19 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AS/400 takes its place at head of the SAA line. (includes relatedarticles on improvements in OS/400 2.0, IBM's image)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Maryfran.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM announces plans to offer certain distributed relationaldatabase capabilities first on the AS/400 minicomputer, making theAS/400 a key platform in its SAA strategy for unifying thecompany's product line.andP;  New 'heterogeneous' protocols will allowdisparate databases, such as SQL/400 and DB2, to communicate witheach other under the VM, OS/2 and OS/400 operating systems.andO;Distributed Relational Data Architecture (DRDA) will be generallyavailable for the OS/400 in Mar 1992 and will allow applicationsto execute multiple SQL requests to other IBM databases.andP;  TheOS/400 2.0 operating system, which will be available in Jun 1991,will fill in many Structured Query Language functions currentlymissing from the AS/400 SQL implementation.andP;  It will providereturn codes, numeric data types and variable length fields.andP;  DRDAwill handle only remote-request and remote-unit-of-work SQLrequests, letting users send a single SQL request out to executeon another system and returning the answer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Planning).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM AS/400 (Minicomputer) (Product development).andO;Topic:     Computer industryMinicomputersData base management systemsStrategic PlanningSAAProtocolProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>